Appraising large office complexes often involves groups of 6-8 people, so I've extensively tested shuttle capacity claims. The disconnect between advertised capacity and practical reality affects both comfort and pricing.

A vehicle advertised as "8-passenger capacity" typically provides comfortable seating for 6 adults with luggage. The capacity number assumes optimal conditions with minimal baggage and passengers of average size. When you factor in airport luggage volumes and varying passenger sizes, practical capacity drops significantly.

This becomes relevant for pricing because many shuttle services charge per vehicle rather than per passenger for groups. If you think you're booking one vehicle for 8 people but actually need two vehicles for comfort and luggage, your cost doubles. The pricing structure isn't deceptive, but capacity assumptions often are.

