## Weather Contingency Policies That Catch People Off-Guard

Colorado weather creates unique operational challenges that most shuttle services handle through policies that aren't clearly communicated until weather events occur. Having coordinated property inspections during blizzards, ice storms, and severe thunderstorms, I've experienced how these policies work in practice.

Most shuttle companies suspend service when road conditions become hazardous, but their definition of "hazardous" varies widely. Some stop operating when snow accumulation reaches 6 inches, others continue until state authorities close highways. The variation means that identically scheduled trips might proceed normally with one company but get canceled with another during the same weather event.

[Colorado Department of Transportation](https://www.codot.gov/) provides real-time road condition updates, but shuttle companies interpret this information differently based on their insurance policies and vehicle capabilities. Chain law requirements particularly affect service decisions because many shuttle vehicles aren't equipped for chain installation or operation.

The timing of weather-related cancellations creates significant passenger impacts. Services typically make cancellation decisions 2-6 hours before scheduled pickup time based on forecasts, but actual weather conditions might improve by travel time. Once canceled, however, rebooking often isn't possible because drivers have been reassigned or taken off schedule.

